meta {
  name: POST /api/chat/:patientId — streaming chat turn (SSE)
  type: http
  seq: 1
}

post {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/api/chat/margaret-chen
  body: json
  auth: none
}

body:json {
  {
    "message": "What medication risks does this patient have?"
  }
}

script:post-response {
  // The done event carries the conversation_id; capture it so the replay
  // request (next in this folder) can reference the same conversation.
  const raw = typeof res.getBody() === 'string' ? res.getBody() : JSON.stringify(res.getBody());
  const match = raw.match(/"conversation_id"\s*:\s*"([^"]+)"/);
  if (match) {
    bru.setVar('conversationId', match[1]);
  }
}

tests {
  test("stream opens with 200 and SSE content type", function() {
    expect(res.getStatus()).to.equal(200);
    expect(String(res.getHeader('content-type'))).to.contain('text/event-stream');
  });

  test("stream ends with a done event carrying cited_fact_ids", function() {
    const raw = typeof res.getBody() === 'string' ? res.getBody() : JSON.stringify(res.getBody());
    expect(raw).to.contain('"type":"done"');
    expect(raw).to.contain('"cited_fact_ids"');
  });
}

docs {
  # Streaming chat turn (spends guarded LLM budget)

  **What it proves:** grounded, citation-gated chat over the patient's
  stored facts, streamed as **Server-Sent Events**. Bruno is not an SSE
  client — it shows the **raw stream** as the response body once the
  turn completes, which is exactly what you want for grading: every
  event is visible verbatim.

  **The raw stream looks like:**

  ```
  data: {"type":"delta","text":"Margaret Chen is on"}

  data: {"type":"delta","text":" hydroxychloroquine ..."}

  data: {"type":"done","conversation_id":"...","cited_fact_ids":["fact-mc-med-001", ...],"invalid_citation_ids":[]}
  ```

  - `delta` events carry incremental answer text (what the panel renders
    token-by-token).
  - The single terminal `done` event carries the `conversation_id` and
    the **validated** citations: `cited_fact_ids` are ids that resolve
    against real stored facts (check them via `/api/facts/margaret-chen`);
    any model-invented ids are quarantined into `invalid_citation_ids`
    rather than presented as citations.
  - On a mid-stream failure you get `data: {"type":"error","error":"chat_failed"}`
    instead — internals are never leaked into the stream.

  **Guards answer as plain JSON before the stream opens**, so clients can
  branch on status codes: `400 {"error":"invalid_message","max_chars":2000}`
  (missing/empty/oversized message), `404 {"error":"patient_not_found"}`,
  `429 {"error":"llm_budget_exceeded","spent_usd":...,"budget_usd":...}`.

  **Request body:** `{"message": "...", "conversation_id": "..."}` —
  `conversation_id` is optional; omit it (as here) to start a new
  conversation, or pass a previous `done` event's id to continue one.

  **Post-response script:** captures `conversation_id` from the `done`
  event into the `conversationId` variable, so the replay request that
  follows targets this very conversation.
}
